<DOC><DOCNO> AP890425-0160 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1931EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Norway-Activists     04-25 0171</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Norway-Activists,0178</SECOND><HEAD>Environmental Activists Mobbed by Norwegian Villagers</HEAD><DATELINE>SOKNDAL, Norway (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A mob of 100 villagers drove offenvironmentalists who had chained themselves to a wharf for 19hours to protest alleged pollution by the town's main employer,news reports said Tuesday.   The four activists were roughed up and sprayed with water fromfirehoses after protesting against the ilmenite mine run by TitaniaA-S, which they say dumps ecologically damaging waste into a nearbyfiord. The mine employs about 350 people in the town of 3,500people.   Environmentalists want the residues dumped on land instead ofthe ocean but Titania has said it obeys state guidelines.   Titania, owned by N.L. Chemicals Inc., of Hightstown, N.J., in1983 became the object of Norway's first major protest against analleged industrial polluter.   ``I don't understand why they were so furious. We have beenholding protests here since 1983 and know many of the villagers,''said Rune Haaland, one of the activists.   No one was injured, according to the Oslo newspaper Aftenposten.</TEXT></DOC>